<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[192,1440,509,662]" lastBlockId="8.[192,1440,221,409]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,335,509,533]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This genus is recognized by the presence of a basal elytral crest with a small tuft of setae (at arrow in 
<figureCitation box="[298,379,541,565]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4c</figureCitation>
, from anterior view in 
<figureCitation box="[646,728,541,565]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4e</figureCitation>
); a pronounced depression behind the elytral crest; pronotal disc nearly impunctate except for row of small, well-defined punctures along posterior constriction (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[192,223,605,629]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="4.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="g" value="4.0">4g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
); pronotum without dorsal tubercles and with broad lateral tubercles positioned posteromedially and apices elevated (
<figureCitation box="[391,503,637,661]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4a, g</figureCitation>
); very broad mesosternal process that is as wide as mesocoxa (
<figureCitation box="[1254,1335,637,661]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4f</figureCitation>
); greatly expanded prosternal process with apex wider than the mesosternal process, closing the procoxal cavities posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[340,421,254,278]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Fig. 4f</figureCitation>
); scape which is mostly evenly cylindrical for the apical ¾ (
<figureCitation box="[1140,1226,254,278]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Fig. 4b</figureCitation>
); absence of erect setae or additional setal tufts on the elytra, legs, antennae, and venter; absence of an elytral carina (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Fig. 4c, e</figureCitation>
); and long first metatarsomere that is nearly the length of the remaining tarsus and pale except for extreme apex (
<figureCitation box="[374,463,352,376]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[199,1422,703,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[192,1441,685,1817]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Luctithonus Lingafelter, new genus. a) Head, anterior view. b) Antennal scape. c) Elytron showing location of basal crest. d) Hind tibia and tarsus. e) Anterior view of elytra showing location and extent of tufts. f) Prosternum and mesosternum. g) Pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3703011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3703011/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Fig. 4d</figureCitation>
). Justification for proposing this new genus is presented in the Remarks, along with comparison to other genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[626,801,385,409]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Acanthocinini">Acanthocinini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
